## 2. The Persecution of Christians

### Current Global Data

Nearly 400 million Christians face high to extreme persecution globally. Believers are killed, imprisoned, and driven from their homes in record numbers across Africa, Asia, and the Middle East. The church faces increasing restriction and hostility even in historically Christian nations.

### What Scripture Declares

**Jesus foretold persecution as normative:**

*"Then shall they deliver you up to be afflicted, and shall kill you: and ye shall be hated of all nations for my name's sake"* (Matthew 24:9).

*"Remember the word that I said unto you, The servant is not greater than his lord. If they have persecuted me, they will also persecute you"* (John 15:20).

*"These things I have spoken unto you, that in me ye might have peace. In the world ye shall have tribulation: but be of good cheer; I have overcome the world"* (John 16:33).

**The pattern was established from the beginning:**

Cain killed Abel because *"his own works were evil, and his brother's righteous"* (1 John 3:12). This establishes the biblical pattern: the wicked persecute the righteous because righteousness condemns wickedness.

Paul taught this as normative: *"Yea, and all that will live godly in Christ Jesus shall suffer persecution"* (2 Timothy 3:12).

**The book of Revelation reveals martyrdom throughout the church age:**

*"And when he had opened the fifth seal, I saw under the altar the souls of them that were slain for the word of God, and for the testimony which they held: And they cried with a loud voice, saying, How long, O Lord, holy and true, dost thou not judge and avenge our blood on them that dwell on the earth? And white robes were given unto every one of them; and it was said unto them, that they should rest yet for a little season, until their fellowservants also and their brethren, that should be killed as they were, should be fulfilled"* (Revelation 6:9-11).

This passage reveals: (1) martyrdom continues throughout history, (2) the martyrs cry out for justice, (3) a specific number of martyrs must be completed before God's judgment falls.

**The saints overcome through faithfulness:**

*"And they overcame him by the blood of the Lamb, and by the word of their testimony; and they loved not their lives unto the death"* (Revelation 12:11).

**Scripture's interpretation of persecution:**

Persecution is not defeat but victory. Christ Himself *"endured the cross, despising the shame"* (Hebrews 12:2). The apostles rejoiced *"that they were counted worthy to suffer shame for his name"* (Acts 5:41). James commands: *"My brethren, count it all joy when ye fall into divers temptations"* (James 1:2). Peter writes: *"Beloved, think it not strange concerning the fiery trial which is to try you, as though some strange thing happened unto you: But rejoice, inasmuch as ye are partakers of Christ's sufferings"* (1 Peter 4:12-13).

The global scope of modern persecution—believers hated "of all nations"—aligns precisely with Christ's prophecy.

