## 5. The Spread of the Gospel

### Current Conditions

Despite persecution and opposition, the gospel continues to spread globally. The church is growing rapidly in Africa, Asia, and Latin America. Bible translation advances. Underground churches multiply in hostile nations. Christianity has become a truly global faith.

### What Scripture Declares

**Jesus promised the gospel would reach all nations:**

*"And this gospel of the kingdom shall be preached in all the world for a witness unto all nations; and then shall the end come"* (Matthew 24:14).

The Greek word for "nations" (ethnos) refers to people groups—tribes, tongues, and peoples—not merely political boundaries.

**The Great Commission guarantees success:**

*"All power is given unto me in heaven and in earth. Go ye therefore, and teach all nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Ghost: Teaching them to observe all things whatsoever I have commanded you: and, lo, I am with you alway, even unto the end of the world"* (Matthew 28:18-20).

Christ commands the mission based on His universal authority and guarantees His presence until "the end of the world" (literally, "the consummation of the age").

**Revelation reveals the outcome:**

*"After this I beheld, and, lo, a great multitude, which no man could number, of all nations, and kindreds, and people, and tongues, stood before the throne, and before the Lamb, clothed with white robes, and palms in their hands"* (Revelation 7:9).

This vision shows the completed harvest—representatives from every segment of humanity worshipping the Lamb. The Great Commission will succeed.

**The church cannot be overcome:**

*"And I say also unto thee, That thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church; and the gates of hell shall not prevail against it"* (Matthew 16:18).

**Gospel growth despite persecution fulfills Scripture:**

*"But I would ye should understand, brethren, that the things which happened unto me have fallen out rather unto the furtherance of the gospel"* (Philippians 1:12).

Paul's imprisonment advanced the gospel. This pattern continues—persecution scatters believers who carry the gospel with them, as happened in Acts 8:1-4: *"They that were scattered abroad went every where preaching the word."*

Isaiah prophesied: *"So shall my word be that goeth forth out of my mouth: it shall not return unto me void, but it shall accomplish that which I please, and it shall prosper in the thing whereto I sent it"* (Isaiah 55:11).

